    "narrative": "Heading into today\u2019s slate, **Corbin Carroll** leads the charge as our strongest play with a 59.06 efficiency score. While he faces a stiff test against Woodruff (2.90 xERA), **Corbin Carroll** benefits from a dynamic platoon advantage and a high-efficiency stolen base environment, as the pitcher's delivery pace heavily favors his aggressive baserunning profile. Similarly, **James Wood** remains a locked-in start at 55.45; while he contends with Peralta\u2019s high-velocity challenge and a sub-optimal park factor, his lead-off spot provides the necessary plate appearance volume to anchor our outfield production.\n\nOur most complex lineup decision centered on the utility spot, where **Kyle Karros** (56.32) narrowly edged out the rest of the bench. **Kyle Karros** benefits significantly from a favorable wind forecast and a platoon-positive matchup against Abbott, which pushed his score into the \"marginal\" start territory. Meanwhile, **Mickey Moniak** was the most notable omission; despite a robust base projection that would have kept him in the conversation, a severe dynamic platoon penalty when facing left-handed pitching effectively neutralized his outlook, cementing his spot on the bench. \n\nThe primary risk today involves the top of the order, specifically **Brice Turang** and **Austin Riley**. **Brice Turang** holds a 58.33 score, but his production is tethered to a tight matchup against Soroka, and any shift in the lineup order could dampen his efficiency. **Austin Riley** carries a 51.50 score, largely suppressed by facing Valdez, though we are banking on his ability to exploit the pitcher's slower delivery to snag a key stolen base. With **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Jose Caballero**, and **Josh Naylor** all idle due to off-days, our bench depth is intentionally thin, making the volatility of **Brice Turang**, **Austin Riley**, **James Wood**, **Corbin Carroll**, and **Kyle Karros** the defining factor for our 5x5 Roto performance today.",
